    "contenu": "The document discusses German wine classification and the history of vineyard classification in Rheingau, Germany. Here's the structured content from the document:\n\n### German Wine Classification Overview\n\n1. **Historical Context**:\n   - The document states that Rheingau is where the long road to German wine classification began.\n   \n2. **Timeline and Development**:\n   - In 1984, Rheingau producers founded an association called **Charta** aiming to classify the best vineyard sites in that region.\n\n3. **Classification Evolution**:\n   - After twenty-five years and various changes, the current classification system is managed by **VDP (Verband Deutscher Prädikatsweingüter)**, which translates to Association of German Prädikat Wine Estates.\n\n4. **VDP Association**:\n   - This is described as an influential association with more than two hundred top estates across Germany. \n\n5. **Regional Variations**:\n   - Despite the national prominence of VDP, there are smaller regional associations in Rheingau that still operate independently.\n   - One example is **Rheingauer Weinbauverband** (Rheingau Winegrowers’ Association) which uses terms similar to VDP for classifying wines.\n\n6. **Classification Terms in Rheingau**:\n   - **Erstes Gewächs** (\"First Growth\"): Signifies top wines similar to terms used by VDP.\n   - **Grosses Gewächs**: Refers to \"Great Growth\" wines and is specifically used to classify wines that are dry.\n\n### Best Producers of the Rheingau\n\n- **Notable Wine Producers**:\n  - August Kesseler\n  - Fred Prinz\n  - Georg Breuer\n  - Josef Leitz\n  - Kloster Eberbach Hessische Staatsweingüter\n  - Künstler\n  - Peter Jakob Kühn\n  - Robert Weil\n  - Schloss Johannisberg\n  - Schloss Schönborn\n  - Spreitzer \n\nThese details encapsulate the approach to wine classification in the Rheingau region, alongside listing some of the top wine producers from the area."
