    "source": "mcgee.pdf_page_69",
    "contenu": "Here is the structured content of the provided document:\n\n### CHEESE\n\n#### Air Travel and Cheese\n- Air travel has brought global attention to different types of cheese that were once considered luxury items for the urban middle class in the United States.\n- A few small producers blend tradition with modern understanding to create superb cheeses with many enthusiasts seeking them out as delightful expressions of ancient craft.\n\n#### The Ingredients of Cheese\n- **Milk**: Primary ingredient, impact of rennet enzymes and microbes essential for acidification and flavoring. Strong influence on cheese character and quality.\n- **Milks**: Concentration of milk during cheese production enhances basic characteristics determined by:\n  - **Species**: Cow's, sheep's, and goat's milk differ considerably. Cow milk is more neutral; sheep and buffalo milk offer higher fat and protein; goat milk leads to crumbly cheeses.\n  - **Breed**: Historical breeding during the Middle Ages led to specialized cheese milks like those from Holstein or Friesian cows bred on standardized feed.\n\n#### Feeding Practices\n- **Feed**: Year-round feeding practices include silage and hay. Pasture grazing affects the milk's flavor complexity through dietary components absorbed by cows.\n- **Seasonality**: Differences in cheese flavor affected by local climate and feeding practices during seasons, impacting the maturity and color of the cheese.\n\n#### Processing \n- **Pasteurized and Raw Milks**: Modern production often involves pasteurization to eliminate disease and spoilage, although this standardizes the taste across different cheeses. High contamination risks with raw milks led to stringent regulations post-1940s by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.\n\nThis document explains various factors impacting cheese production, including the influence of milk sources, feeding practices, and modern safety standards in cheese pasteurization."
