    "source": "inconnu_2367",
    "contenu": "The document provided is titled \"MILK AND DAIRY PRODUCTS\" and covers a section primarily focused on the industrialization and development of ice cream in America. It delves into the cultural popularity, the process of production, and the structural elements that define the consistency and quality of ice cream. Below is the structured content of the document:\n\n---\n\n### MILK AND DAIRY PRODUCTS\n\n#### In America, a Food for the Masses\n- **History in America**: Ice cream was transformed into a popular delicacy in America for the masses starting from awkward small-batch procedures. It highlights a significant innovation in 1843 by Nancy Johnson of Philadelphia who invented a more efficient ice cream maker.\n- **Industrial Advances**: The text describes how a Baltimore milk dealer named Jacob Fussell leveraged his surplus cream to produce ice cream on a mass scale in the 1850s, leading eventually to large quantities being manufactured and a booming popularity by 1900.\n\n#### The Industrialization of Ice Cream\n- **Post-World War II Developments**: The industry shifted to produce ice cream using modern technology that allowed faster and colder freezing, leading to smoother textures. Manufacturers started using stabilizers and additives to enhance consistency and reduce cost.\n\n#### The Structure and Consistency of Ice Cream\n- **Components**:\n  - **Ice Crystals**: Formed from water in the mix, these are crucial in giving ice cream its firm structure.\n  - **Concentrated Cream**: This phase contains most of the mass including milk fat and proteins. It’s essential for the creamy texture.\n  - **Air**: Incorporated during the mixing process, air inflates the volume of ice cream making it light and easy to scoop. The amount of air added impacts the overall volume and texture, referred to as \"overrun.\"\n\n- **Quality Indicators**: \n  - Texture is determined by the size of ice crystals and air content.\n  - \"Overrun\" affects the density; higher overrun means lighter ice cream.\n  \n#### Market Trends\n- **Consumption**: Americans consume substantially more ice cream than Europeans, amounting to nearly 20 quarts/liters per person annually.\n- **Economic Aspects**: Utilization of surplus production and artificial flavors has made ice cream both economical and diverse in varieties available at different price points.\n\n---\n\nThis structured summary offers an overview of the key points discussed in the document on ice cream's historical context, manufacturing advancements, structural components, and consumption trends."
