    "source": "396118758-Understanding-Wines-Explaining-Style-and-Quality.pdf_page_162",
    "contenu": "The document is an informative text describing the wine sector in Chile. It is structured under several headers, each focusing on different aspects such as grape varieties, specific regional wines, and the features of various wine-producing areas. Below is a structured summary of the content provided in the document under each heading:\n\n### Red Grape Varieties\n- **Merlot:** Medium-bodied and fruity, successful on export markets, with fuller-bodied, complex versions also found. Especially successful in warmer, sunniest sites.\n- **Carmenère:** A late ripening variety that is most successful in the warmest and sunniest sites. Known for full-bodied wines with high levels of tannin, balancing black fruit character and herbal aromas.\n- **Syrah:** Planted across various Chilean sites, known for lighter, peppery notes in cooler climates and more intense black fruit flavors and fuller body in warmer sites.\n- **Pinot Noir:** Known for greater intensity of black fruit flavors and fuller body, mainly found in cooler locations like San Antonio and Casablanca Valleys.\n\n### White Grape Varieties \n- Dominated by two international varieties, **Sauvignon Blanc** and **Chardonnay**.\n- **Sauvignon Blanc:** Thrives in cooler vineyard sites such as those in Casablanca and San Antonio Valleys, yielding high acidity wines with fruity, floral, and sometimes herbaceous notes.\n- **Chardonnay:** Yields full, expressive wines with high acidity, mostly found in Casablanca Valley; famous for oaked styles with ripe fruit and oak flavors.\n\n### Aconcagua Region\n- Known for its wine production but is the second smallest wine region in Chile, divided into three sub-regions with the Aconcagua Valley being the primary area.\n\n### Coquimbo Region\n- Borders the Atacama Desert to the north, divided into three winemaking sub-regions: **Elqui Valley, Limarí Valley,** and **Choapa Valley**. Highlights include:\n  - **Elqui Valley:** Smaller compared to others, known for high-quality plantings and challenges like water scarcity.\n  - **Limarí Valley:** Known for producing structured Chardonnays and other wines with minerality and bright fruit flavors.\n\n### Regions and Wines Overview:\n- **Coquimbo:** Noted for high-quality vineyards with high-quality yields, despite challenges from water scarcity.\n- **Central Valley and Southern:** Not directly detailed in the provided text but mentioned in relation to overall Chilean wine production.\n\n### Geographic Overview:\n- The document includes a map displaying the regions of Chile known for wine production, from north to south, and categorizes them by altitude, which affects the temperature and vineyard conditions, ultimately influencing the style and characteristics of the wines produced in each area. The map marks the specific valleys and regions, providing a visual understanding of the geographic division of wine production areas in Chile.\n\nThis summary captures the integral details regarding the varietals and the regional characteristics prominent in Chile's wine industry as described in the document."
