    "source": "396118758-Understanding-Wines-Explaining-Style-and-Quality.pdf_page_64",
    "contenu": "---\n**White and Sweet Winemaking**\n---\n\nThis chapter focuses on winemaking options for white wine and reviews high volume, inexpensive, and premium wines. It emphasizes less involvement in white winemaking than in red winemaking. Key grape varieties discussed include Chardonnay, Sauvignon Blanc, Riesling, and Pinot Grigio. The chapter also touches on sweet winemaking which is primarily associated with white wine.\n\n### Important Options in White Winemaking\n- **Skin Contact**: Short contact time with skins is employed to reduce the risk of oxidation and impurities, improving purity and delicacy of the wine.\n- **Clarity of the Juice**: Ensuring the juice is free from fragments of cells, skins, and pulp is crucial. Techniques such as settling, centrifugation, and filtration are used to refine and clarify the juice before fermentation.\n  \n### Fermentation Temperature and Vessel\n- **Temperature**: Optimal fermentation temperatures for white wines are between 12°C and 22°C. Temperatures too low can result in poor aromas and reduced varietal characters.\n- **Vessel Types**: Stainless steel and high-quality veneers are common due to their ability to dissipate heat effectively and control fermentation temperatures.\n\n### Post-fermentation and Maturation Options\n- **Storage**: White wine can be stored in inert vessels with or without the addition of oak staves or chips, depending on the desired complexity and flavor.\n- **Maturation**: Focus may be on the fine lees to add texture and flavor, and options like Batonnage and MLF (Malolactic Fermentation) can be employed to alter the wine's style.\n\n### Blending\nBlending can help improve consistency, balance, and create a specific style in white wines. It might involve using different batches of wine, varying amounts of lees contact, or different aging methods to achieve a desired complexity.\n\n### Clarification and Stabilisation\nMost white wines undergo some form of clarification and stabilization to ensure brightness and stability in the final product. Techniques often include filtration and cold stabilization to minimize sediments and haziness.\n\nThis overview presents a careful consideration of various processes and options in the production of white and sweet wines, focusing on quality, purity, and stylistic precision."
